timeline.bodyText:
Do we need this? From what I understand from the javadocs, these two are equivalent
duplicator.duplicate(true);
duplicator.close();
duplicator.duplicate();
duplicator.close();

replies.bodyText:
Yes, they are equivalent.
Actually, we don't have to call close in the first example.
duplicator.duplicate(true).subscribe(...);
// Equivalent to 
duplicator.duplicate().subscribe(...);
duplicator.close();
We need the first code for the response in RetryingClient. We have to return the last HttpResonse to the user API, so when the last response is subscribed and complete, the resources are cleaned up. (We don't know when we need to call close() because we don't know the duplicate HttpResponse is subscribed by the user or not.)
We need the second one for the request. The duplicated HttpRequest is already subscribed by the HttpRequestSubscriber and we don't want to duplicate anymore so just call close().

I guess some users might want to release the duplicator automatically. How about extending SafeCloseable?
public interface HttpRequestDuplicator extends StreamMessageDuplicator<HttpObject>, SafeCloseable {
    ...
    @Override
    void close();
}

